daily logs in `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` format\n- Files include `memory.md` (core facts), `opinions.md` (subjective judgments), and `entities/` (entity database)\n\n### 2. **2026 AI Programming Trends - Agent Memory Systems**\n- **Persistent memory systems** solve the \"re-explaining architecture\" problem\n- AI assistants maintain **cross-conversation project awareness** including:\n  - Project context: Past architecture decisions and reasoning\n  - Personal preferences: React hooks vs class components, naming conventions\n  - Team knowledge: Module ownership, deployment processes\n- Addresses the biggest developer complaint with AI: having to re-explain the codebase every session\n\n### 3. **文心快码 (Comate) - Project Memory**\n- Features **\"Project Memory\"** for project-level memory\n- Enables new employees to quickly ramp up on old projects\n- Solves **knowledge gaps** caused by staff turnover\n- Described as \"organization-level capability\" for coding agents\n\n### 4. **Claude Code Memory System**\n- **Three-tier memory structure**:\n  - `./CLAUDE.md` - Shared team memory (committed to version control)\n  - `./CLAUDE.local.md` - Personal workspace notes (gitignored)\n  - `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` - Global user preferences across all projects\n- Uses recursive search strategy for efficient context loading\n\n### 5. **\"project-memory\" Skill Tutorial (January 2026)**\n- Describes building a project memory skill for Claude Code\n- Addresses \"AI forgetfulness\" problem where developers must re-solve the same bugs\n- Without memory, each chat session starts from zero\n- Multiple platforms now support Agentic Skills (Claude Code, Codex, GitHub Copilot, etc.)\n\n### 6. **Memory Review Systems**\n- Workflow: Agent proposes memory → Appears in chat → User reviews/approves → Added to workspace long-term memory\n- Uses turn summaries with pending memory notifications\n- Allows editing before saving to workspace\n\nThe core theme across these sources is that **workspace/project memory is becoming a critical feature for AI code agents in 2026**, moving beyond single-session interactions to maintain persistent context across conversations and team collaboration.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
